.TH HSH 1 "May 2026" "1.0" "Simple Shell Man Page"

.SH NAME
hsh \- simple UNIX command line interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
[\fIcommand\fR]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX shell that reads and executes commands from standard input.
It replicates the core behavior of
.B /bin/sh
and supports both interactive and non-interactive modes.

In interactive mode, the shell displays a prompt
.B ($)
and waits for user input. In non-interactive mode, commands are read from a pipe or file.

.SH INVOCATION
.TP
.B Interactive mode:
.nf
$ ./hsh
($) command [arguments]
.fi

.TP
.B Non-interactive mode:
.nf
$ echo "command" | ./hsh
$ cat script_file | ./hsh
.fi

.SH BUILT-IN COMMANDS

.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell. Terminates the current shell session.

.TP
.B env
Print the current environment variables to standard output, one per line.

.SH EXECUTION

When a command is entered,
.B hsh
searches for the executable in the directories listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable. If found, it forks a child process and uses
.BR execve (2)
to run the command. The parent process waits for the child to complete before prompting again.

If the command is not found,
.B hsh
prints an error message to standard error in the following format:

.nf
    ./hsh: 1: command: not found
.fi

.SH EXAMPLES

.TP
Run a command in interactive mode:
.nf
($) /bin/ls
hsh main.c shell.c
.fi

.TP
Run a command in non-interactive mode:
.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
hsh main.c shell.c
.fi

.TP
Print environment variables:
.nf
($) env
PATH=/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin
HOME=/root
...
.fi

.SH ENVIRONMENT

.TP
.B PATH
Colon-separated list of directories to search for commands.

.TP
.B HOME
The home directory of the current user.

.SH EXIT STATUS

.TP
.B 0
Command executed successfully.

.TP
.B 1
Command not found or execution failed.

.TP
.B 2
Usage error.

